# ECS Patterns

This document defines Entity-Component-System (ECS) architecture patterns for game development. ECS promotes data-oriented design, cache efficiency, and clear separation of concerns.

---

## Core Concepts

### Entity

An entity is a unique ID. It has no behavior or data; it is a handle to a set of components.

```cpp
using Entity = uint32_t;
const Entity NULL_ENTITY = 0;
```

### Component

A component is a plain data struct. No logic, no methods beyond trivial accessors. Components are stored in contiguous arrays (SoA or AoS) for cache efficiency.

```cpp
struct Position {
    float x, y, z;
};

struct Velocity {
    float vx, vy, vz;
};

struct Health {
    int current;
    int max;
};
```

### System

A system is a function that operates on entities matching a specific component query. Systems are stateless and process entities in batches.

```cpp
void movement_system(Query<Position, Velocity>& query, float dt) {
    for (auto [entity, pos, vel] : query) {
        pos.x += vel.vx * dt;
        pos.y += vel.vy * dt;
        pos.z += vel.vz * dt;
    }
}
```

---

## Archetypes

### Definition

An archetype is the set of component types attached to an entity. Entities with the same archetype are stored together for efficient iteration.

| Archetype | Components | Use Case |
|-----------|-------------|----------|
| Static | Transform | Environment props |
| Dynamic | Transform, Velocity, Collider | Moving objects |
| Character | Transform, Velocity, Health, Input | Player/NPC |
| Projectile | Transform, Velocity, Lifetime | Bullets, effects |

### Archetype Transitions

When adding or removing a component, the entity moves to a new archetype. This is a structural change and should be deferred to end of frame when possible.

```cpp
// Defer structural changes
world.defer([&]() {
    world.add_component(entity, Health{100, 100});
});
```

---

## System Ordering

### Dependency Graph

Systems have implicit dependencies based on read/write component access. Order systems to respect data flow.

```
InputSystem (writes Input)
    -> MovementSystem (reads Input, Velocity; writes Position)
    -> CollisionSystem (reads Position, Collider; writes CollisionEvents)
    -> HealthSystem (reads CollisionEvents; writes Health)
    -> RenderSystem (reads Position, Sprite)
```

### Execution Order Rules

1. Systems that write a component must run before systems that read it (for same-frame use).
2. Parallel systems: no shared writes. Multiple readers of same data can run in parallel.
3. Document system order in a central registry or config.

### Example Ordering Config

```yaml
systems:
  - input
  - movement
  - collision
  - health
  - ai
  - render
```

